  "prompt": "Can I keep savings account if my status changes to NRI? What happens to my PPF and NPS accounts?",
  "response": "If your status changes to Non-Resident Indian (NRI), there are specific rules and regulations regarding your existing financial accounts in India, including savings accounts, Public Provident Fund (PPF), and National Pension System (NPS). Here's a breakdown:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **Savings Account**\n   - **You cannot continue with a regular savings account** once your status changes to NRI.\n   - You will need to convert your existing savings account to an **NRE (Non-Resident External) or NRO (Non-Resident Ordinary) account**.\n     - **NRE Account**: Funds in this account are fully repatriable (can be transferred abroad), and the interest earned is tax-free in India.\n     - **NRO Account**: This account is used for managing income earned in India (e.g., rent, dividends). The funds are partially repatriable, and interest earned is taxable in India.\n   - You must inform your bank about your NRI status to initiate the conversion process.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Public Provident Fund (PPF)**\n   - **You can continue your existing PPF account** even after becoming an NRI.\n   - However, **you cannot open a new PPF account** once your status changes to NRI.\n   - The account will continue to earn interest and will mature as per the original 15-year term.\n   - At maturity, you can either close the account or extend it in blocks of 5 years (with or without contributions).\n   - Note that PPF contributions made after becoming an NRI are **not eligible for tax deductions** under Section 80C of the Income Tax Act.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **National Pension System (NPS)**\n   - **You can continue your NPS account** after becoming an NRI.\n   - You can continue contributing to your NPS account, and the contributions will be treated as per NRI rules.\n   - **Repatriation**:\n     - Up to 60% of the corpus (withdrawn at retirement) can be repatriated abroad after deducting applicable taxes.\n     - The remaining 40% must be used to purchase an annuity, and the income from the annuity can be repatriated.\n   - Ensure that your PAN (Permanent Account Number) and bank account details are updated to reflect your NRI status.\n\n---\n\n### Additional Points to Consider:\n   - **Taxation**: NRIs are subject to different tax rules in India. Income earned in India (e.g., interest, rent) may be taxable, and you may need to file an income tax return in India.\n   - **KYC Updates**: Notify all financial institutions (banks, PPF, NPS) about your change in residential status to ensure compliance with regulations.\n   - **Foreign Exchange Management Act (FEMA)**: Ensure that all transactions comply with FEMA guidelines, especially regarding repatriation of funds.\n\n---\n\nIf you're unsure about any specific aspect, it\u2019s advisable to consult with a financial advisor or tax expert who specializes in NRI matters.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
